📄 Week 4 – Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) and Data Profiling
📌 Overview

During the fourth week, we focused on Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) and understanding the dataset before performing further analysis. We also learned about Key Performance Indicators (KPIs) and data profiling tools available in Power Query.

📊 Topics Covered
1️⃣ Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

EDA is the process of analyzing and understanding a dataset before performing detailed analysis or building dashboards. It helps identify patterns, detect errors, and understand the structure of data.

2️⃣ Types of Data

We learned about three main types of data:

Categorical Data – Represents categories or labels (e.g., Priority, Category)

Numeric Data – Represents measurable values (e.g., sales, response time)

Time Series Data – Data recorded over time (e.g., tickets per day)

3️⃣ Steps in EDA

The main steps followed in EDA are:

Understanding the data – Checking columns, data types, and structure

Cleaning the data – Removing duplicates and handling missing values

Detecting and removing outliers – Identifying extreme values that affect analysis

Finding relationships between columns – Understanding how variables are related

4️⃣ Data Profiling Tools in Power Query

We explored the View tab in Power Query, which provides important tools:

🔹 Column Quality

Shows percentage of valid values, errors, and empty values

Helps quickly identify data issues

🔹 Column Distribution

Shows frequency of values in a column

Helps identify duplicates and patterns

🔹 Column Profile

Provides detailed statistics such as:

Minimum value

Maximum value

Average

Value distribution

These tools help in quickly understanding the dataset without manual calculations.

5️⃣ Outliers

We learned about outliers, which are extreme or unusual values that differ significantly from the rest of the data.

Outliers can affect analysis results

They need to be identified and handled properly

6️⃣ Key Performance Indicators (KPIs)

We also discussed KPIs, which are measurable values used to evaluate performance.

Examples:

Total Sales

Average Response Time

Number of Tickets Resolved

Profit Margin

KPIs help in tracking performance and making data-driven decisions.

🎯 Learning Outcome

By the end of this week, we understood how to:

Perform exploratory data analysis

Identify data types and data quality issues

Use Power Query profiling tools

Detect outliers

Define and use KPIs for analysis

✅ Conclusion

Week 4 helped us understand that before performing analysis, it is important to explore and understand the dataset using EDA techniques. Proper data understanding leads to more accurate insights and better decision-making.
